questions.question_text: In neurobiology, what is a synapse?

options.A: A specialized junction where a neuron transmits mechanical or thermal signals to another neuron, muscle cell, or gland cell.
options.B: A specialized junction where a glial cell transmits electrical or chemical signals to another neuron, muscle cell, or gland cell.
options.C: A specialized junction where a neuron transmits electrical or chemical signals to another neuron, muscle cell, or gland cell.
options.D: A specialized junction where a neuron generates electrical or chemical signals within its own cell body and dendrites.

questions.question_text: In neurobiology, what is a dendrite?

options.A: A branched extension of a neuron that transmits electrochemical signals to other neurons via synapses.
options.B: A branched extension of a neuron that receives electrochemical signals from other neurons via gap junctions.
options.C: A branched extension of a glial cell that receives electrochemical signals from other neurons via synapses.
options.D: A branched extension of a neuron that receives electrochemical signals from other neurons via synapses.

questions.question_text: In neurobiology, what is an axon?

options.A: A long, slender projection of a glial cell that conducts electrical impulses away from the cell body.
options.B: A long, slender projection of a neuron that conducts electrical impulses away from the cell body.
options.C: A short, branched projection of a neuron that conducts electrical impulses away from the cell body.
options.D: A long, slender projection of a neuron that conducts electrical impulses toward the cell body.

questions.question_text: In the nervous system, what is the primary function of myelin?

options.A: An insulating sheath around axons formed by glial cells that decreases the speed of electrical signal transmission.
options.B: An insulating sheath around axons formed by glial cells that increases the speed of electrical signal transmission.
options.C: An insulating sheath around dendrites formed by glial cells that increases the speed of electrical signal transmission.
options.D: An insulating sheath around axons formed by neurons that increases the speed of chemical signal transmission.

questions.question_text: In neurobiology, what is an action potential?

options.A: A rapid, transient reversal of the chemical concentration gradient that propagates along a neuron's axon as a nerve impulse.
options.B: A rapid, transient reversal of the electrical membrane potential that propagates along a neuron's axon as a nerve impulse.
options.C: A gradual, sustained reversal of the electrical membrane potential that propagates along a neuron's axon as a nerve impulse.
options.D: A rapid, transient reversal of the electrical membrane potential that propagates along a neuron's dendrite as a nerve impulse.

questions.question_text: In neurobiology, what is an ion channel?

options.A: A pore-forming membrane protein that allows all molecules to pass through the cell membrane down their concentration gradient.
options.B: A pore-forming membrane protein that allows specific ions to pass through the cell membrane down their electrochemical gradient.
options.C: A pore-forming cytoplasmic protein that allows specific ions to pass through the cell membrane down their electrochemical gradient.
options.D: A pore-forming membrane protein that actively pumps specific ions through the cell membrane against their electrochemical gradient.

questions.question_text: Dopamine is a neurotransmitter. What chemical class does it belong to?

options.A: A catecholamine, synthesized from the amino acid tryptophan via L-DOPA, functioning as both neurotransmitter and hormone.
options.B: An indolamine, synthesized from the amino acid tryptophan via L-DOPA, functioning as both neurotransmitter and hormone.
options.C: A catecholamine, synthesized from the amino acid tyrosine via L-DOPA, functioning as both neurotransmitter and hormone.
options.D: A catecholamine, synthesized from the amino acid tyrosine via serotonin, functioning as both neurotransmitter and hormone.

questions.question_text: What is neurogenesis?

options.A: The process by which existing neurons are repaired by neural stem cells in the nervous system.
options.B: The process by which new neurons are produced from neural stem cells in the nervous system.
options.C: The process by which new neurons are eliminated through programmed cell death in the nervous system.
options.D: The process by which new glial cells are produced from neural stem cells in the nervous system.

questions.question_text: What is the blood-brain barrier?

options.A: A highly selective semipermeable border of endothelial cells that prevents harmful substances in the blood from entering the brain.
options.B: A highly selective semipermeable border of glial cells that prevents harmful substances in the blood from entering the brain.
options.C: A highly selective semipermeable border of endothelial cells that prevents cerebrospinal fluid from exiting the brain.
options.D: A nonselective permeable border of endothelial cells that allows all substances in the blood to freely enter the brain.

questions.question_text: What is the autonomic nervous system?

options.A: A division of the nervous system that unconsciously regulates internal organs, smooth muscle, and glands, controlling functions like memory and language.
options.B: A division of the nervous system that unconsciously regulates sensory receptors, smooth muscle, and glands, controlling functions like vision and hearing.
options.C: A division of the nervous system that unconsciously regulates internal organs, smooth muscle, and glands, controlling functions like heart rate and digestion.
options.D: A division of the nervous system that consciously regulates skeletal muscles and joints, controlling functions like locomotion and posture.

questions.question_text: What are sensory neurons?

options.A: Afferent neurons that convert environmental stimuli into action potentials and transmit signals between interneurons within the spinal cord.
options.B: Efferent neurons that convert environmental stimuli into action potentials and transmit signals from the periphery to the central nervous system.
options.C: Afferent neurons that convert environmental stimuli into action potentials and transmit signals from the periphery to the central nervous system.
options.D: Afferent neurons that convert motor commands into action potentials and transmit signals from the central nervous system to the periphery.

questions.question_text: What are motor neurons?

options.A: Efferent neurons whose axons project from the brain or spinal cord to detect stimuli from muscles and glands, enabling sensory feedback.
options.B: Efferent neurons whose dendrites project from the brain or spinal cord to control muscles and glands, enabling only voluntary movement.
options.C: Afferent neurons whose axons project from the brain or spinal cord to control muscles and glands, enabling voluntary and involuntary movement.
options.D: Efferent neurons whose axons project from the brain or spinal cord to control muscles and glands, enabling voluntary and involuntary movement.

questions.question_text: In the peripheral nervous system, what is a nerve?

options.A: An enclosed cable-like bundle of axons (nerve fibers) that provides a common pathway for producing neurotransmitters within peripheral organs.
options.B: An enclosed cable-like bundle of dendrites (nerve fibers) that provides a common pathway for transmitting electrochemical impulses to or from peripheral organs.
options.C: A single elongated axon (nerve fiber) that provides an independent pathway for transmitting electrochemical impulses to or from peripheral organs.
options.D: An enclosed cable-like bundle of axons (nerve fibers) that provides a common pathway for transmitting electrochemical impulses to or from peripheral organs.

questions.question_text: Long-term potentiation (LTP) depends on a specific kinase activated by calcium entry through NMDA receptors. Which kinase is considered critical for the induction of early-phase LTP?

options.A: Calcium/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase IV (CaMKIV), which autophosphorylates and increases AMPA receptor insertion at the presynaptic membrane
options.B: Mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK), which autophosphorylates and increases AMPA receptor insertion at the postsynaptic membrane
options.C: Calcium/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase II (CaMKII), which autophosphorylates and increases AMPA receptor insertion at the postsynaptic membrane
options.D: Calcium/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase II (CaMKII), which autophosphorylates and increases NMDA receptor insertion at the postsynaptic membrane

questions.question_text: The NMDA receptor acts as a coincidence detector because it requires two conditions to be met simultaneously for channel opening. What are these two conditions?

options.A: Glutamate and co-agonist glycine must bind the receptor, and the postsynaptic membrane must be sufficiently depolarized to expel the magnesium block from the channel pore.
options.B: Glutamate and co-agonist glycine must bind the receptor, and the postsynaptic membrane must be sufficiently hyperpolarized to attract sodium ions into the channel pore.
options.C: GABA and co-agonist glycine must bind the receptor, and the postsynaptic membrane must be sufficiently depolarized to expel the calcium block from the channel pore.
options.D: Glutamate and co-agonist acetylcholine must bind the receptor, and the postsynaptic membrane must be sufficiently depolarized to expel the magnesium block from the channel pore.

questions.question_text: GABA is the chief inhibitory neurotransmitter in the mature mammalian brain. What enzyme catalyzes the synthesis of GABA from its amino acid precursor?

options.A: Glutamine synthetase synthesizes GABA by removing an amino group from glutamine.
options.B: Glutamic acid decarboxylase (GAD) synthesizes GABA by removing a carboxyl group from aspartate.
options.C: GABA transaminase synthesizes GABA by removing a carboxyl group from glutamate.
options.D: Glutamic acid decarboxylase (GAD) synthesizes GABA by removing a carboxyl group from glutamate.

questions.question_text: Oligodendrocytes myelinate axons in the central nervous system. Which cell performs the equivalent myelination function in the peripheral nervous system?

options.A: Astrocytes myelinate peripheral axons, but unlike oligodendrocytes each astrocyte wraps only one axonal segment.
options.B: Schwann cells myelinate peripheral axons, but unlike oligodendrocytes each Schwann cell wraps only one axonal segment.
options.C: Schwann cells myelinate peripheral axons, and like oligodendrocytes each Schwann cell can wrap up to 40 axonal segments.
options.D: Satellite glial cells myelinate peripheral axons, but unlike oligodendrocytes each satellite cell wraps only one axonal segment.

questions.question_text: Astrocytes are identified histologically by their expression of a characteristic intermediate filament protein. What is this widely used astrocyte marker?

options.A: Ionized calcium-binding adapter molecule 1 (Iba1), an intermediate filament expressed abundantly in both fibrous and protoplasmic astrocytes.
options.B: Glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP), an intermediate filament expressed abundantly in both fibrous and protoplasmic astrocytes.
options.C: Neurofilament heavy chain (NF-H), an intermediate filament expressed abundantly in both fibrous and protoplasmic astrocytes.
options.D: Myelin basic protein (MBP), an intermediate filament expressed abundantly in both fibrous and protoplasmic astrocytes.

questions.question_text: Microglia serve as the resident immune cells of the central nervous system. From which embryonic structure do microglia originate during development?

options.A: Microglia originate from primitive macrophage precursors in the yolk sac, similar to other glia which are also derived from mesoderm.
options.B: Microglia originate from primitive macrophage precursors in the bone marrow, distinguishing them from other glia derived from neuroectoderm.
options.C: Microglia originate from neural crest progenitor cells in the neural tube, distinguishing them from other glia derived from neuroectoderm.
options.D: Microglia originate from primitive macrophage precursors in the yolk sac, distinguishing them from other glia derived from neuroectoderm.

questions.question_text: The sodium-potassium pump is an electrogenic transporter essential for maintaining resting membrane potential. What is its ion transport stoichiometry per ATP hydrolyzed?

options.A: Three sodium ions are exported and two potassium ions are imported per ATP, producing a net export of one positive charge.
options.B: Two sodium ions are exported and three potassium ions are imported per ATP, producing a net import of one positive charge.
options.C: Three sodium ions are exported and three potassium ions are imported per ATP, producing no net charge movement.
options.D: Two sodium ions are exported and two potassium ions are imported per ATP, producing no net charge movement.

questions.question_text: At nodes of Ranvier, the axolemma is enriched with specific ion channels and cytoskeletal adaptor proteins. Which protein anchors sodium channels at these nodes?

options.A: Ankyrin-G, a cytoskeletal adaptor protein that clusters voltage-gated sodium channels at the node.
options.B: Spectrin-alpha, a cytoskeletal adaptor protein that clusters voltage-gated potassium channels at the node.
options.C: Dystrophin, a cytoskeletal adaptor protein that clusters voltage-gated sodium channels at the node.
options.D: Ankyrin-G, a transmembrane receptor protein that clusters ligand-gated sodium channels at the node.

questions.question_text: At the neuromuscular junction, what type of receptor does acetylcholine bind to on the sarcolemma to depolarize the muscle fiber?

options.A: Nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChRs), which are ligand-gated ion channels on the postjunctional folds.
options.B: Nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChRs), which are ligand-gated ion channels on the prejunctional membrane.
options.C: Nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChRs), which are G-protein-coupled receptors on the postjunctional folds.
options.D: Muscarinic acetylcholine receptors (mAChRs), which are ligand-gated ion channels on the postjunctional folds.

questions.question_text: Schwann cells are also known by what alternate histological name, and how many axons does each myelinating Schwann cell insulate?

options.A: Neurolemmocytes; each myelinating Schwann cell provides insulation to one fascicle of axons.
options.B: Neurolemmocytes; each myelinating Schwann cell provides insulation to only one axon.
options.C: Oligolemmocytes; each myelinating Schwann cell provides insulation to only one axon.
options.D: Neurolemmocytes; each myelinating Schwann cell provides insulation to multiple axons simultaneously.

questions.question_text: Synaptic vesicle fusion with the presynaptic membrane requires a protein complex. What is this complex called, and which toxin specifically damages its vesicular component?

options.A: The clathrin complex; tetanus toxin specifically damages VAMP, the vesicle-associated membrane protein (v-SNARE).
options.B: The SNARE complex; tetanus toxin specifically damages syntaxin, the target membrane protein (t-SNARE).
options.C: The SNARE complex; tetanus toxin specifically damages VAMP, the vesicle-associated membrane protein (v-SNARE).
options.D: The SNARE complex; botulinum toxin exclusively damages VAMP, the vesicle-associated membrane protein (v-SNARE).

questions.question_text: A growth cone has three structural domains. What cytoskeletal element primarily composes the peripheral domain, and what composes the central domain?

options.A: The peripheral domain is primarily microtubule-based, while the central domain is primarily actin-based.
options.B: The peripheral domain is primarily actin-based, while the central domain is primarily intermediate-filament-based.
options.C: The peripheral domain is primarily actin-based, while the central domain is primarily microtubule-based.
options.D: The peripheral domain is primarily neurofilament-based, while the central domain is primarily microtubule-based.

questions.question_text: Central pattern generators can produce rhythmic output through reciprocal inhibition between neuron groups. What is the specific term for this circuit architecture?

options.A: A half-center oscillator, where two neuron groups reciprocally excite each other to produce alternating activity.
options.B: A half-center oscillator, where two neuron groups reciprocally inhibit each other to produce alternating activity.
options.C: A half-center oscillator, where two neuron groups reciprocally inhibit each other to produce synchronous activity.
options.D: A pacemaker-follower circuit, where two neuron groups reciprocally inhibit each other to produce alternating activity.

questions.question_text: In saltatory conduction, why does myelination increase action potential speed rather than simply insulating the axon like electrical tape on a wire?

options.A: Myelin forces ion exchange to occur at every internode, so the action potential regenerates at closely spaced points rather than continuously along the membrane.
options.B: Myelin forces ion exchange to occur only at nodes of Ranvier, so the action potential travels passively without regeneration at any point along the axon.
options.C: Myelin forces ion exchange to occur only at the axon hillock, so the action potential regenerates at one point rather than continuously along the membrane.
options.D: Myelin forces ion exchange to occur only at nodes of Ranvier, so the action potential regenerates at discrete points rather than continuously along the membrane.

questions.question_text: In the neuronal SNARE complex that drives synaptic vesicle fusion, which proteins contribute the four alpha-helices of the core bundle?

options.A: Syntaxin contributes one helix, synaptobrevin (VAMP) contributes one helix, and synaptotagmin contributes two helices to form the four-helix bundle.
options.B: Syntaxin contributes one helix, synaptobrevin (VAMP) contributes one helix, and SNAP-25 contributes two helices to form the four-helix bundle.
options.C: Syntaxin contributes one helix, SNAP-25 contributes one helix, and synaptobrevin (VAMP) contributes two helices to form the four-helix bundle.
options.D: Syntaxin contributes two helices, synaptobrevin (VAMP) contributes one helix, and SNAP-25 contributes one helix to form the four-helix bundle.

questions.question_text: How do endocannabinoids like anandamide and 2-AG differ from classical neurotransmitters in their direction of signaling at a synapse?

options.A: They are stored in vesicles in the postsynaptic neuron and travel backward to bind presynaptic CB2 receptors, acting as retrograde messengers.
options.B: They are synthesized on demand in the presynaptic neuron and travel forward to bind postsynaptic CB1 receptors, acting as anterograde messengers.
options.C: They are synthesized on demand in the postsynaptic neuron and travel backward to bind presynaptic NMDA receptors, acting as retrograde messengers.
options.D: They are synthesized on demand in the postsynaptic neuron and travel backward to bind presynaptic CB1 receptors, acting as retrograde messengers.

questions.question_text: How do pro-neurotrophins differ from mature neurotrophins in their receptor binding and effect on neuronal survival?

options.A: Pro-neurotrophins preferentially bind p75NTR with high affinity and promote apoptosis, whereas mature neurotrophins bind Trk receptors to promote survival.
options.B: Pro-neurotrophins preferentially bind Trk receptors with high affinity and promote apoptosis, whereas mature neurotrophins bind p75NTR to promote survival.
options.C: Pro-neurotrophins preferentially bind p75NTR with high affinity and promote survival, whereas mature neurotrophins bind Trk receptors to promote apoptosis.
options.D: Pro-neurotrophins preferentially bind p75NTR with low affinity and promote apoptosis, whereas mature neurotrophins bind Trk receptors to promote differentiation only.

questions.question_text: Why does axon regeneration after Wallerian degeneration succeed in the PNS but largely fail in the CNS?

options.A: Oligodendrocytes rapidly clear myelin debris and form guidance tubes for regrowing axons, while CNS Schwann cells fail to clear inhibitory myelin debris.
options.B: Schwann cells slowly clear myelin debris but secrete abundant growth factors, while CNS oligodendrocytes rapidly clear debris but form impenetrable glial scars.
options.C: Schwann cells rapidly clear myelin debris and form guidance tubes for regrowing axons, while CNS oligodendrocytes fail to clear inhibitory myelin debris.
options.D: Schwann cells rapidly clear myelin debris and form guidance tubes for regrowing axons, while CNS oligodendrocytes clear debris but secrete growth inhibitors.

questions.question_text: In patch clamp electrophysiology, what is the gigaseal and why is it essential for recording single ion channel currents?

options.A: A seal of 10-100 gigaohm resistance between pipette and cell membrane that electrically isolates the patch, minimizing background noise.
options.B: A seal of 10-100 gigaohm resistance between pipette and bath electrode that electrically isolates the recording circuit, minimizing background noise.
options.C: A seal of 10-100 gigaohm resistance between pipette and cell membrane that amplifies the channel current signal, increasing recording strength.
options.D: A seal of 10-100 megaohm resistance between pipette and cell membrane that electrically isolates the patch, minimizing background noise.

questions.question_text: In optogenetics, how are neurons made responsive to light stimulation?

options.A: By expressing light-sensitive ion channels such as channelrhodopsin, which depolarize the cell membrane when illuminated.
options.B: By expressing light-sensitive G-protein coupled receptors such as channelrhodopsin, which hyperpolarize the cell membrane when illuminated.
options.C: By expressing light-sensitive ion channels such as halorhodopsin, which depolarize the cell membrane when illuminated.
options.D: By expressing light-sensitive ion pumps such as channelrhodopsin, which open gap junctions between cells when illuminated.

questions.question_text: During axon guidance, what role does the secreted molecule Netrin play, and which receptors mediate its effects?

options.A: Netrin acts as both an attractant and repellent for growth cones, signaling through Eph and Neuropilin receptors.
options.B: Netrin acts as both an attractant and repellent for growth cones, signaling through DCC and UNC-5 receptors.
options.C: Netrin acts as both an attractant and repellent for growth cones, signaling through Plexin and Robo receptors.
options.D: Netrin acts exclusively as a repellent for growth cones, signaling through Robo and UNC-5 receptors.

questions.question_text: What cellular mechanism regulates the opening of critical periods of plasticity in brain development?

options.A: Maturation of somatostatin-positive inhibitory interneurons, driven by factors like NGF and Pax6 that activate GABAergic inhibitory circuits.
options.B: Maturation of parvalbumin-positive inhibitory interneurons, driven by factors like BDNF and Otx2 that activate GABAergic inhibitory circuits.
options.C: Maturation of parvalbumin-positive excitatory interneurons, driven by factors like BDNF and Otx2 that activate glutamatergic excitatory circuits.
options.D: Maturation of parvalbumin-positive inhibitory interneurons, driven by factors like BDNF and Otx2 that activate cholinergic modulatory circuits.

questions.question_text: During synaptic pruning, what determines which synaptic connections are eliminated versus retained?

options.A: Inhibitory synapses are preferentially retained, while excitatory synapses are eliminated, following a balance and prune principle.
options.B: Frequently used synapses are strengthened and retained, while rarely activated synapses are eliminated, following a use it or lose it principle.
options.C: Synapses formed earliest in development are retained, while later-formed synapses are eliminated, following a first in last out principle.
options.D: Frequently used synapses are tagged for elimination, while rarely activated synapses are stabilized, following a use it and lose it principle.

questions.question_text: In excitotoxicity, what is the primary intracellular mechanism by which excessive glutamate receptor activation leads to neuronal death?

options.A: Excess sodium influx through NMDA and AMPA receptors activates destructive enzymes like calpain, phospholipases, and endonucleases.
options.B: Excess calcium influx through NMDA and AMPA receptors activates destructive enzymes like calpain, phospholipases, and endonucleases.
options.C: Excess calcium influx through NMDA and AMPA receptors triggers immediate mitochondrial ATP overproduction and membrane rupture.
options.D: Excess calcium influx through kainate and nicotinic receptors activates destructive enzymes like calpain, phospholipases, and endonucleases.

questions.question_text: Neural crest cells arise through what developmental process, and what diverse cell types do they generate?

options.A: They arise via epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition from the neural tube, generating melanocytes, peripheral neurons, craniofacial cartilage, and adrenal medulla cells.
options.B: They arise via epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition from the notochord, generating melanocytes, peripheral neurons, craniofacial cartilage, and adrenal medulla cells.
options.C: They arise via mesenchymal-to-epithelial transition from the neural tube, generating melanocytes, peripheral neurons, craniofacial cartilage, and adrenal medulla cells.
options.D: They arise via epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition from the neural tube, generating astrocytes, central motor neurons, craniofacial cartilage, and adrenal cortex cells.

questions.question_text: In quantal neurotransmitter release, what is the role of synaptotagmin in the molecular machinery that triggers vesicle fusion at the presynaptic terminal?

options.A: Synaptotagmin acts as a voltage sensor that, upon detecting membrane depolarization, interacts with the SNARE complex to promote vesicle fusion and exocytosis.
options.B: Synaptotagmin acts as a calcium sensor that, upon binding calcium ions, interacts with the SNARE complex to promote vesicle fusion and exocytosis.
options.C: Synaptotagmin acts as a calcium buffer that, upon sequestering calcium ions, dissociates from the SNARE complex to inhibit vesicle fusion and exocytosis.
options.D: Synaptotagmin acts as a calcium sensor that, upon binding calcium ions, interacts with the clathrin complex to promote vesicle fusion and endocytosis.

questions.question_text: What distinguishes channelopathies from diseases caused by ion pump dysfunction, and how does this relate to the biophysical mechanism of ion movement?

options.A: Channelopathies involve ion pumps that move ions rapidly via active transport down electrochemical gradients, whereas channel disorders affect slow passive transport against gradients.
options.B: Channelopathies involve ion channels that move ions slowly via active transport against electrochemical gradients, whereas pump disorders affect rapid passive transport down gradients.
options.C: Channelopathies involve ion channels that move ions rapidly via passive transport down electrochemical gradients, whereas pump disorders affect rapid passive transport along gradients.
options.D: Channelopathies involve ion channels that move ions rapidly via passive transport down electrochemical gradients, whereas pump disorders affect slow active transport against gradients.

questions.question_text: In the adult mammalian brain, neural stem cells in the subventricular zone generate new neurons that migrate to a specific destination. What is their pathway and final target?

options.A: They migrate through the corpus callosum to the olfactory bulb, where they differentiate into projection neurons participating in olfaction.
options.B: They migrate through the rostral migratory stream to the dentate gyrus, where they differentiate into granule cells participating in memory.
options.C: They migrate through the rostral migratory stream to the olfactory bulb, where they differentiate into astrocytes participating in gliotransmission.
options.D: They migrate through the rostral migratory stream to the olfactory bulb, where they differentiate into interneurons participating in olfaction.

questions.question_text: How do perineuronal nets regulate synaptic transmission at parvalbumin-positive interneurons, specifically with respect to glutamate receptor dynamics at the cell surface?

options.A: PNNs act as lateral diffusion barriers for AMPA receptors, permeabilizing the neuronal surface and enhancing synaptic exchange of desensitized receptors for naive ones.
options.B: PNNs act as lateral diffusion barriers for NMDA receptors, compartmentalizing the neuronal surface and limiting synaptic exchange of desensitized receptors for naive ones.
options.C: PNNs act as lateral diffusion barriers for AMPA receptors, compartmentalizing the neuronal surface and limiting synaptic exchange of desensitized receptors for naive ones.
options.D: PNNs act as endocytic scaffolds for AMPA receptors, compartmentalizing the neuronal surface and accelerating internalization of desensitized receptors into recycling endosomes.

questions.question_text: In the tripartite synapse model, astrocytes respond to neuronal activity with a specific intracellular signaling event. What is this event and how does it enable bidirectional communication?

options.A: Astrocytes produce sustained intracellular calcium elevations via voltage-gated channels, enabling them to detect neurotransmitters and release cytokines that modulate neuronal excitability.
options.B: Astrocytes produce transient intracellular sodium elevations via endoplasmic reticulum stores, enabling them to detect neurotransmitters and release gliotransmitters that modulate neuronal excitability.
options.C: Astrocytes produce transient intracellular calcium elevations via mitochondrial stores, enabling them to detect gliotransmitters and release neurotransmitters that modulate synaptic vesicle cycling.
options.D: Astrocytes produce transient intracellular calcium elevations via endoplasmic reticulum stores, enabling them to detect neurotransmitters and release gliotransmitters that modulate neuronal excitability.

questions.question_text: How did Eccles' 1976 reformulation of Dale's principle differ from the common earlier interpretation, and why was this revision significant for understanding co-transmission?

options.A: Eccles added or substances, allowing neurons to release multiple transmitters while asserting that different sets are released at each of a neuron's synapses.
options.B: Eccles added or substances, restricting neurons to releasing only one transmitter while asserting the same one is released at all of a neuron's synapses.
options.C: Eccles removed the same transmitter, allowing neurons to release a single transmitter while asserting it varies across different synaptic targets of a neuron.
options.D: Eccles added or substances, allowing neurons to release multiple transmitters while asserting the same set is released at all of a neuron's synapses.

questions.question_text: The enteric nervous system contains roughly 500 million neurons. What is the primary embryological origin of these neurons, distinguishing them from most other peripheral autonomic neurons?

options.A: Neural tube cells, specifically ventral neural tube progenitors that migrate to the gut during embryonic development.
options.B: Neural crest cells, specifically vagal neural crest progenitors that migrate to the gut during embryonic development.
options.C: Mesodermal precursors, specifically splanchnic mesoderm progenitors that differentiate within the gut during embryonic development.
options.D: Neural crest cells, specifically sacral neural crest progenitors that exclusively colonize the gut during postnatal development.

questions.question_text: Conscious and nonconscious proprioception travel via distinct ascending pathways. Which pathway carries nonconscious proprioceptive information, and where does it terminate?

options.A: The dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway carries nonconscious proprioception to the cerebellum for motor coordination.
options.B: The lateral spinothalamic tract carries nonconscious proprioception to the cerebellum for motor coordination.
options.C: The dorsal and ventral spinocerebellar tracts carry nonconscious proprioception to the cerebellum for motor coordination.
options.D: The dorsal and ventral spinocerebellar tracts carry nonconscious proprioception to the somatosensory cortex for motor coordination.

questions.question_text: The glial scar both protects and hinders CNS recovery. Which molecular class secreted by reactive astrocytes into the extracellular matrix is most directly responsible for inhibiting axonal regeneration?

options.A: Keratan sulfate proteoglycans, along with fibronectin, which chemically repel extending axonal growth cones.
options.B: Heparan sulfate proteoglycans, along with tenascin C, which chemically attract extending axonal growth cones.
options.C: Chondroitin sulfate proteoglycans, along with laminin, which physically degrade extending axonal growth cones.
options.D: Chondroitin sulfate proteoglycans, along with tenascin C, which chemically repel extending axonal growth cones.

questions.question_text: The normal cellular prion protein PrPC and the infectious isoform PrPSc differ structurally. What specific secondary structure change occurs during conversion, and what property does PrPSc gain?

options.A: PrPSc acquires a higher proportion of beta-sheet structure replacing alpha-helices, gaining susceptibility to phospholipase C cleavage.
options.B: PrPSc acquires a higher proportion of beta-sheet structure replacing alpha-helices, gaining resistance to proteinase K digestion.
options.C: PrPSc acquires a higher proportion of alpha-helical structure replacing beta-sheets, gaining resistance to proteinase K digestion.
options.D: PrPSc acquires a higher proportion of beta-turn structure replacing alpha-helices, gaining resistance to proteinase K digestion.

questions.question_text: Hubel and Wiesel extended Mountcastle's columnar organization concept to the visual cortex. What does a hypercolumn in visual cortex specifically represent in terms of receptive field properties?

options.A: A hypercolumn contains a single preferred orientation value shared across all receptive field parameters and both ocular dominance columns.
options.B: A hypercolumn contains a full set of values for all receptive field parameters, including all orientations but only one ocular dominance column.
options.C: A hypercolumn contains a full set of spatial frequency values for all receptive field parameters, excluding orientation and ocular dominance columns.
options.D: A hypercolumn contains a full set of values for all receptive field parameters, including all orientations and both ocular dominance columns.

questions.question_text: When endoplasmic reticulum calcium stores are depleted during neuronal signaling, what mechanism restores intracellular calcium, and which proteins mediate this process?

options.A: Store-operated calcium entry occurs via CRAC channels, mediated by STIM1 sensing mitochondrial depletion and activating Orai1 channels in the ER membrane.
options.B: Store-operated calcium entry occurs via CRAC channels, mediated by STIM1 sensing ER depletion and activating Orai1 channels in the plasma membrane.
options.C: Store-operated calcium entry occurs via CRAC channels, mediated by calmodulin sensing ER depletion and activating TRPC channels in the plasma membrane.
options.D: Voltage-gated calcium entry occurs via L-type channels, mediated by STIM1 sensing ER depletion and activating Orai1 channels in the plasma membrane.
